@node blizz "'Using Chipsaver with a Blizzard A1230/A1260 card"
@prev main
@next main

(don't forget to read the warning at the end of this page)

Well,without entering into the details,let's say that those Blizzard '030/'060
card aren't simple ones (unlike the RAM/020 boards).NO....They have a ROM that
takes the control of the reset.

One of the side effects of such a 'powerful' installation is that NOTHING
can survive the reset with these cards! (fast memory is added VERY LATE to
the exec memlists....too bad).
It's ok for viruses,but it's quite annoying for recoverable ram disks
(RAD: etc...),and chipsaver :-(

Well,recently I got the excellent BlizzMagic package.It's 'just' (hem)
a program like "rekick" etc but specially for Blizzards(!)

One of the very nice side effects of this tool is that using the FASTEXEC
option,you will be able to use your RAD:,chipsaver etc like with any
other Amiga!!

I included the BlizzMagic archive in the package I hope the author won't
feel offended (should he? hu hu ;)

So the only thing you have to do is get a 3.1 rom (v40).
I now use a grabbed rom from a CD-32 (v40.60) and it works fine.
DO NOT USE PRIOR VERSIONS,THEY WERE UNSTABLE BETA-VERSIONS.

That's it!!!

Note:Of course all this is valid ONLY if you already used the HardRemap
feature of these cards (JUMPER OFF) otherwise......

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                WARNING
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
As Blizzmagic is a (good but yet) HACK,there are unusual interactions with
ChipSaver (or any other resident tools),that do not occur with a "normal"
system.

I tried to catch these problems but solved them only partially.
The result now is that  YOU CANNOT REMOVE CHIPSAVER ONCE YOU'VE INSTALLED
IT,IF YOU'RE USING BLIZZMAGIC:if you try to do so,ChipSaver will remove
itself normally,but at the next reset,Blizzmagic will react with an endless
red screen+flashing led (checksum error I guess).Read the following technical
info only if you're interested in exec's heavy reset-magic ;-)

some of my debugging adventure:
-------------------------------
When using blizzmagic,I was surprised to see that Scout indicated TWO
chipsaver resident modules.Where did I fail?! Well,nowhere! when using
a bare A1200 chipmem,no problem....
So after some tracing,it appeared that these 2 resident modules were the
same one (same address etc),one being the classical,recognized from the
KickTagPtr list,and the other,coming from the resmodules list! Which is not
normal...usually the resmodules entries don't appear after the reset.Only
the kicktagptr do (& they're inserted in the resmodules list ONLY during 
reset).(am I totally wrong?! :)
So my rough guess is that blizzmagic has some kind of internal execbase
fake/copy somewhere,probably in relation with the FASTEXEC stuff.It may have
an internal checksum,so that's why removing ChipSaver from the REAL
execbase doesn't affect BlizzMagic internal parameters=>messes up at the
reset & blow up with a checksum failure.
Maybe all this is not entirely exact,but it musn't be far from truth,and at
least the result is the same ;-(
All I've done is add a scan of the resmodules list during the reset
& remove (!) the ChipSaver entry in it (if existing).So only the 'normal'
 entry will appear in Scout etc...


@endnode
@endnode